prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
This is a simple continuum observation of point source photometry. Observations for all the bands must be packed in 1 day, although any date is OK. Because the reference band for pointing is Band 6, We propose sequential band switchings as follows: B3 (B4,6 ON) -> B4 (B3 OFF, B6,7 ON) -> B6 (B4 OFF, B7,8 ON) -> B7 (B6,8 ON) -> B8. For bands that are off, the time to fully thermally-stabilize them from an off state is 15 minutes. On the other hand, it takes about 30 minutes every 1 Science Goal. Therefore, above frequency switching strategy can be done without additional overhead.
We would like to user-defined calibrations using multiple quasars for amplitude calibration (see Scientific Justification in detail). However, OT encountered unexpected error in time estimate and validation. This is a known problem according to helpdesk. Helpdesk suggest that my request of user-defined calibration is described in this Techinical Justification. We would like to observe additional calibrators: 3C273, 3C279 (separated by less than 20 deg from the target), and PG1222+216 (9 deg) for all the Science Goals.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
Our result from ALMA cycle-0 observation [2011.0.00754.S] revealed a spectral break at ~200 GHz in the continuum spectrum of the M87 nucleus. This is a very important result because the spectral break indicates line-of-sight toward a black hole shadow should be transparent at higher frequencies; we can perform imaging of the black hole shadow successfully with future submm VLBIs without being hampered by an optically-thick photosphere.
We propose a cycle-2 observation to confirm this discovery. A new observation is required because (1) the spectral break frequency was found around the coverage of band-4, which was not implemented during the cycle-0/1, and (2) by using multiple calibrators, we will confirm that the residual error of calibration for a frequency-dependent atmospheric absorption is not affected significantly to the observed radio spectrum. Our cycle-2 observation demands 10 frequency settings in the band-3/4/6/7/8 within one day. This study will not be possible without the broad frequency coverage or the fast-band-switching capability of ALMA. The sensitivities of cycle-2 allow us to conduct such observations in reasonable execution time (<5 hours).
